Sec. 40001: Authorizes a $24.6 billion special appropriation to the Coast Guard for FY2025–2029, earmarked for 13 specific procurement and infrastructure items—e.g., $4.3 billion for new Offshore Patrol Cutters, $1.1 billion for fixed-wing aircraft, and $425 million for rebuilding the enlisted boot camp barracks at Cape May. The funds are exempt from normal annual caps and remain available until 2029.

Sec. 40002: Extends the FCC’s competitive-bidding authority for spectrum auctions to September 2034 and mandates the Commerce Department to identify and auction at least 500 MHz of federal spectrum in the 1.3–10.5 GHz band, with 200 MHz to be auctioned within four years; $50 million is appropriated to support this analysis through 2034.

Sec. 40003: Provides $10.5 billion over five years (FY2025–2029) for FAA modernization—$4.75 billion for telecom upgrades, $3 billion for radar replacement, $1.9 billion for a new ARTCC, and $1 billion for TRACON consolidations—plus $100 million for advanced controller-training tech, with quarterly reporting to Congress.

Sec. 40004: Establishes user-fee schedules for space launches and reentries under the FAA’s Office of Commercial Space Transportation, starting at $30,000 per launch in 2026 and rising to $200,000 by 2033, with 70 % of collections deposited into a dedicated fund for licensing operations.

Sec. 40005: Allocates $9.995 billion through 2032 for NASA’s Moon-to-Mars program—$2.6 billion for the Gateway, $4.1 billion for SLS Artemis IV/V cores, $1 billion for ISS operations, and $1 billion for infrastructure upgrades at the five major NASA centers, with 50 % of funds obligated by September 2028.

Sec. 40006: Eliminates civil penalties for corporate average fuel-economy violations by setting the per-vehicle fine at $0.00, effective immediately for all model years lacking a Department of Transportation penalty notification.

Sec. 40007: Increases the annual lease-payment obligation of the Metropolitan Washington Airports Authority to the U.S. Treasury from $3 million (in 1987 dollars) to a fixed $15 million per year starting in 2027, with a mandatory 10-year renegotiation clause to maintain that amount.

Sec. 40008: Rescinds any unobligated balances from FY2022 appropriations for NOAA, FAA, and other DOT programs, effectively clawing back unspent funds.

Sec. 40009: Cuts the annual federal subsidy for the Brand USA tourism-promotion program from $100 million to $20 million starting in FY2025.

Sec. 40010: Rescinds any unspent balances from the 2022 CHIPS Act’s $500 million grant program for alternative-fuel aviation technologies.

Sec. 40011: Permanently rescinds $850 million of unobligated CHIPS Act funds originally allocated for domestic semiconductor supply-chain initiatives. [end of text]


